00:25:40,747 --> 00:25:42,207
you wanna crush me, too?"

455
00:25:42,290 --> 00:25:43,124
"Yup."

456
00:25:43,208 --> 00:25:46,086
They had a practice game in Monte Carlo.

457
00:25:47,045 --> 00:25:52,217
And Magic and Barkley's team
got off to a big lead.

458
00:25:52,759 --> 00:25:55,011
- Ball!
- Whoo! Yes!

459
00:25:55,637 --> 00:25:59,724
That was the greatest basketball, I think,
that we all were involved in.

460
00:26:00,392 --> 00:26:04,437
Great passing, great shooting,
great defense.

461
00:26:05,480 --> 00:26:08,191
All NBA players going back and forth
at each other.

462
00:26:09,693 --> 00:26:10,527
Let's go.

463
00:26:10,610 --> 00:26:13,029
There was real trash talking
going on from...

464
00:26:13,113 --> 00:26:15,282
Particularly from Charles and Magic
toward Michael.

465
00:26:15,365 --> 00:26:16,491
Don't be cheatin' on me!

466
00:26:16,575 --> 00:26:19,035
Magic always got under Michael's skin
for some reason.

467
00:26:20,620 --> 00:26:22,831
Right there.
Right back at it, baby.

468
00:26:22,914 --> 00:26:24,916
I'm coming after you. Free throws.

469
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:28,378
It's all right! That's all right!
Here we go!

470
00:26:30,463 --> 00:26:32,799
God damn.
You don't play no defense. That's weak.

471
00:26:32,882 --> 00:26:35,468
We ain't in Chicago Stadium
no more.

472
00:26:35,552 --> 00:26:38,597
We're up about eight points, I think.
Something like that.

473
00:26:39,180 --> 00:26:40,557
And I went over and tapped him.

474
00:26:41,683 --> 00:26:46,229
I said, "Look, man, if you don't turn into
Air Jordan, we gonna blow you out."

475
00:26:47,480 --> 00:26:49,566
Man, what did I say that for?

476
00:26:49,649 --> 00:26:53,403
Michael proceeded to score
every time down the court.

477
00:26:54,237 --> 00:26:56,114
He was like,
"You wanna know who the guy is?

478
00:26:56,197 --> 00:26:57,197
Here's who the guy is."

479
00:26:57,866 --> 00:26:59,951
He broke the huddle,
hit a three. Bam!

480
00:27:00,035 --> 00:27:02,621
Came back down, hit another three. Bam!

481
00:27:02,704 --> 00:27:05,915
He came through the middle
and just shook everybody. Bam!

482
00:27:06,666 --> 00:27:09,586
Before we know, they was up two.

483
00:27:10,086 --> 00:27:11,171
Yes!

484
00:27:11,254 --> 00:27:12,088
Yes!

485
00:27:12,172 --> 00:27:16,134
He drove to the basket
and the referee called a foul,

486
00:27:16,718 --> 00:27:20,096
and Magic threw the ball up
to the top of the arena

487
00:27:20,639 --> 00:27:22,724
and was screaming about,

488
00:27:22,807 --> 00:27:26,770
"Just like the NBA, he gets every call!
Same thing over here!"

489
00:27:26,853 --> 00:27:29,773
All they did was move
the Bulls stadium right here.

490
00:27:29,856 --> 00:27:32,442
That's all they did. That's all they did.

491
00:27:32,525 --> 00:27:34,653
This is the '90s.

492
00:27:34,736 --> 00:27:38,448
I don't care if it's the '90s
or not. What's that supposed to mean?

493
00:27:38,531 --> 00:27:40,408
This is the '90s.

494
00:27:43,453 --> 00:27:45,205
How you like that ass kicking
we gave y'all?

495
00:27:45,288 --> 00:27:46,873
No, no, no. Come on, now.

496
00:27:48,083 --> 00:27:52,212
After the practice, they get
on the bus to go back to the hotel.

497
00:27:53,171 --> 00:27:57,133
And for a couple of minutes,
there's no talking.

498
00:27:58,176 --> 00:28:01,346
When we got on the bus,
it was... It was... Whoo! Man.

499
00:28:01,429 --> 00:28:05,308
And all of a sudden,
Magic says to Barkley,

500
00:28:05,392 --> 00:28:08,269
"Hey, Charles, I guess we
shouldn't have pissed the man off."

501
00:28:08,353 --> 00:28:12,065
And then everybody, "This is
the greatest practice ever. We love this!"

502
00:28:12,649 --> 00:28:13,692
Ooh, la, la!

503
00:28:13,775 --> 00:28:19,239
After that game, everyone
acknowledged we're in a new era.

504
00:28:19,864 --> 00:28:22,826
Michael Jordan was the alpha-alpha.

505
00:28:24,452 --> 00:28:25,537
Period.

506
00:28:25,620 --> 00:28:26,722
- Michael!
- What's up?

507
00:28:26,746 --> 00:28:29,874
Game on the line,
who would take the last shot?

508
00:28:29,958 --> 00:28:30,958
Me.

509
00:28:32,127 --> 00:28:33,920
- That's a dumb question. Me.
- Yeah.

510
00:28:35,463 --> 00:28:37,924
<i>But now,
a cavalry rides to the rescue.</i>

511
00:28:38,007 --> 00:28:39,467
<i>As the Olympics open to NBA players,</i>

512
00:28:39,551 --> 00:28:42,637
<i>the US sends
the greatest team ever assembled.</i>

513
00:28:43,513 --> 00:28:46,349
<i>The United States will be
the overwhelming favorite in Barcelona.</i>

514
00:28:46,433 --> 00:28:49,477
Among the competition, though,
there's one team that stands out.

515
00:28:49,561 --> 00:28:51,813
Like the USA, it's loaded with talent.

516
00:28:51,896 --> 00:28:54,524
Croatia has built a basketball powerhouse.

517
00:28:57,777 --> 00:29:02,282
There's Toni Kukoc, the 6'10" wizard
they call the left-handed Magic Johnson.

518
00:29:02,365 --> 00:29:05,577
A lot of excitement about
tomorrow's game against Croatia,

519
00:29:05,660 --> 00:29:09,456
our first chance to see Toni Kukoc
against this kind of competition.

520
00:29:09,539 --> 00:29:11,583
What do you know about him and them?

521
00:29:11,666 --> 00:29:12,876
I don't know a lot about him,

522
00:29:12,959 --> 00:29:16,629
but if you listen to Michael and Scottie,
they know a whole lot about him

523
00:29:16,713 --> 00:29:19,007
because, apparently,
there was some mixed emotions

524
00:29:19,090 --> 00:29:21,217
about him going to Chicago.

525
00:29:22,093 --> 00:29:27,974
With the second pick in the second round,
the Chicago Bulls select Toni Kukoc.

526
00:29:28,057 --> 00:29:31,644
Toni's certainly an outstanding
young prospect.

527
00:29:32,228 --> 00:29:34,731
I also think
that he's an outstanding young man.

528
00:29:36,024 --> 00:29:38,318
But after I was drafted
by the Bulls,

529
00:29:38,401 --> 00:29:41,738
the situation at home was not so great,

530
00:29:42,405 --> 00:29:44,115
'cause of the war and everything.

531
00:29:44,699 --> 00:29:47,368
<i>Yugoslavia is, of course,
a country divided.</i>

532
00:29:47,452 --> 00:29:50,663
<i>In June, two of its republics,
Croatia and Slovenia,</i>

533
00:29:50,747 --> 00:29:54,167
<i>declared their independence,
igniting a bloody civil war.</i>

534
00:29:55,168 --> 00:29:58,630
I just decided to play
a couple more years in Europe first.

535
00:29:59,881 --> 00:30:06,596
Just to be there, kind of,
just to, uh, not take off completely.

536
00:30:07,347 --> 00:30:10,350
And I was making
considerably more in Europe

537
00:30:10,433 --> 00:30:13,269
than I would make
my first couple of years here.

538
00:30:13,853 --> 00:30:17,732
We're not talking a little money,
we're talking a couple million.

539
00:30:18,316 --> 00:30:22,362
Jerry went over to watch Toni play
in what was then Yugoslavia

540
00:30:22,445 --> 00:30:27,158
and said Toni Kukoc is gonna be
the future of the Chicago Bulls.

541
00:30:29,536 --> 00:30:33,373
Jerry was fawning
over Toni so much

542
00:30:33,456 --> 00:30:37,293
while our team here
was winning championships.

543
00:30:37,377 --> 00:30:41,798
And it just... It rubbed a lot of
the players the wrong way, unfortunately.

544
00:30:41,881 --> 00:30:45,385
The timing of this Kukoc thing
is where the problem has been all along.

545
00:30:45,468 --> 00:30:47,720
He went out to negotiate with Kukoc

546
00:30:47,804 --> 00:30:50,849
while Pippen was waiting to sign
the deal that he's currently under.

547
00:30:50,932 --> 00:30:53,476
They put him on hold
while they negotiated with Kukoc.

548
00:30:53,560 --> 00:30:58,064
Krause, you know, he's willing to put
someone in front of his actual kids,

549
00:30:58,147 --> 00:31:01,985
who have given him everything
that we could give him.

550
00:31:03,862 --> 00:31:07,740
At that time, I have no idea
what was going on with the Bulls.

551
00:31:07,824 --> 00:31:11,911
I don't know the frictions between
Scottie and Jerry, Michael and Jerry.

552
00:31:12,871 --> 00:31:17,792
So, going to the Olympics,
I kinda thought everything was okay.

553
00:31:18,835 --> 00:31:21,963
<i>The major story line
that carries into this game</i>

554
00:31:22,046 --> 00:31:24,132
<i>involves European star Toni Kukoc.</i>

555
00:31:24,215 --> 00:31:27,719
In the Dream Team locker room,
before the first game against Croatia,

556
00:31:27,802 --> 00:31:32,599
Michael just said, "Hey, guys. Kukoc.
Leave him for Scottie and me."

557
00:31:34,851 --> 00:31:37,061
<i>Kukoc being played
by Pippen.</i>

558
00:31:38,354 --> 00:31:40,189
<i>And Kukoc went to the reverse.</i>

559
00:31:41,107 --> 00:31:43,651
<i>There's Jordan with the step on Kukoc.</i>

560
00:31:44,360 --> 00:31:47,447
<i>Kukoc trying to return it,
Pippen with the steal.</i>

561
00:31:48,031 --> 00:31:49,699
Well, I didn't play a good game.

562
00:31:49,782 --> 00:31:54,412
I got surprised
by how strict they played defense.

563
00:31:54,495 --> 00:31:58,708
I didn't expect somebody to be next to me
literally the whole game.

564
00:31:58,791 --> 00:32:03,463
<i>Jordan and Pippen are intent
on showing their superiority.</i>

565
00:32:04,297 --> 00:32:08,593
Toni Kukoc became a great teammate
and I love Toni Kukoc for who he is,

566
00:32:09,093 --> 00:32:11,804
but the way he was introduced
to me and Scottie was...

567
00:32:11,888 --> 00:32:14,891
I didn't appreciate it
and it drove my energy.

568
00:32:14,974 --> 00:32:17,352
<i>And at this point,
Toni Kukoc...</i>

569
00:32:17,936 --> 00:32:21,397
<i>zero points, zero rebounds
for the Croatian team.</i>

570
00:32:21,481 --> 00:32:23,650
<i>Jordan and Pippen have been all over him.</i>

571
00:32:23,733 --> 00:32:27,528
I felt bad for Toni and I thought
Michael and Scottie were out of line.

572
00:32:27,612 --> 00:32:28,821
He was terrified.

573
00:32:29,697 --> 00:32:31,699
<i>And it's Pippen again.</i>

574
00:32:31,783 --> 00:32:33,368
<i>Here's Pippen...</i>

575
00:32:34,035 --> 00:32:37,705
<i>Third foul.
Pippen with a setup from below.</i>

576
00:32:37,789 --> 00:32:40,708
<i>Well, to this point,
it has been all Scottie Pippen.</i>

577
00:32:42,335 --> 00:32:45,421
Jerry paved the way
for a lot of hell on Toni Kukoc.

578
00:32:46,965 --> 00:32:48,800
Not only was it just me and Michael,

579
00:32:48,883 --> 00:32:53,388
but every guy on that Olympic team
looked at that kid and felt like,

580
00:32:53,471 --> 00:32:56,891
"He may not even think about coming
to the NBA after he played against us."

581
00:32:56,975 --> 00:32:58,559
<i>The pressure continues.</i>

582
00:32:59,560 --> 00:33:03,523
It wasn't anything personally
about Toni...

583
00:33:04,107 --> 00:33:08,277
but we were gonna do everything
that we could to make Jerry look bad.

584
00:33:08,361 --> 00:33:10,029
<i>Eighteen off a 19-5 run.</i>

585
00:33:10,113 --> 00:33:13,449
<i>Jordan rejected Kukoc.
Here's a three-on-two.</i>

586
00:33:13,533 --> 00:33:15,618
<i>Pippen, all the way!</i>

587
00:33:17,954 --> 00:33:19,831
<i>A 33-point victory.</i>

588
00:33:19,914 --> 00:33:22,875
<i>Pippen also holding
Toni Kukoc to four points.</i>

589
00:33:23,459 --> 00:33:28,172
I know Scottie was a little pissed about
all the publicity surrounding Kukoc,

590
00:33:28,256 --> 00:33:32,510
and he proved today that if they gonna
give anybody in Chicago any more money,

591
00:33:32,593 --> 00:33:33,720
it better be him.

592
00:33:34,470 --> 00:33:37,890
I still hear talk that he just had
a bad game, he was nervous, but...

593
00:33:38,516 --> 00:33:42,270
if he's that nervous, then he can't
come to the NBA and play two games.

594
00:33:42,353 --> 00:33:43,521
They didn't know me.

595
00:33:43,604 --> 00:33:47,191
I don't see a reason...
Why would they try and take it on me?

596
00:33:47,275 --> 00:33:48,693
They don't know me at all.

597
00:33:48,776 --> 00:33:51,237
That's the first time we meet.

598
00:33:51,320 --> 00:33:54,240
Scottie says he doesn't
think he could play in the NBA.

599
00:33:54,323 --> 00:33:55,323
Do you agree?

600
00:33:56,159 --> 00:33:59,537
Yeah, that's a little bit unfair
and unjust to him. You gotta realize,

601
00:33:59,620 --> 00:34:03,124
the guy was playing against 11
of the best players in the league.

602
00:34:03,207 --> 00:34:05,793
Once we were in the finals,
because obviously...

603
00:34:05,877 --> 00:34:10,673
the United States is gonna be
the second finalist, then we'll play.

604
00:34:10,757 --> 00:34:12,884
<i>Coming up shortly,
the Dream Team,</i>

605
00:34:12,967 --> 00:34:16,596
<i>the US Men's Basketball Team,
will take on Croatia for the gold medal.</i>

606
00:34:17,597 --> 00:34:20,767
This is the second meeting
between the United States and Croatia.

607
00:34:20,850 --> 00:34:25,563
The last time they met, last week,
the United States won by 33 points.

608
00:34:25,646 --> 00:34:27,486
The second game
when we played them,

609
00:34:27,523 --> 00:34:29,043
Kukoc came back and I give him credit.

610
00:34:29,108 --> 00:34:32,445
He came back and played a much better game
than he did the first game.

611
00:34:35,990 --> 00:34:38,326
<i>Toni Kukoc certainly
has turned it around</i>

612
00:34:38,409 --> 00:34:42,872
<i>from his performance in the earlier
meeting against the United States.</i>

613
00:34:42,955 --> 00:34:47,043
Americans didn't understand
how tough people like Toni Kukoc were.

614
00:34:47,126 --> 00:34:47,960
They had no idea.

615
00:34:48,044 --> 00:34:51,547
Some people have no idea
about the war-torn situations,

616
00:34:51,631 --> 00:34:56,761
and the poverty and the oppression
that guys like Kukoc came from,

617
00:34:56,844 --> 00:34:58,805
that produced them, that hardened them.

618
00:34:58,888 --> 00:35:00,640
So, it was stupid to call him soft.

619
00:35:01,641 --> 00:35:05,103
He had to fight to gain their respect...
and he did it.

620
00:35:06,020 --> 00:35:08,523
To come back after being
totally emasculated,

621
00:35:08,606 --> 00:35:10,650
it showed me a lot about Toni Kukoc.

622
00:35:10,733 --> 00:35:14,362
<i>Kukoc now has 16 points,
six assists.</i>

623
00:35:14,904 --> 00:35:17,073
I remember Michael coming
to the locker room saying,

624
00:35:17,156 --> 00:35:19,951
"He played pretty well.
He's tougher than we thought."

625
00:35:24,288 --> 00:35:29,961
<i>...117-85 and they have,
as expected, won the gold.</i>

626
00:35:30,586 --> 00:35:33,381
The team won the '92 Olympics.

627
00:35:33,464 --> 00:35:35,842
And then, Michael decided

628
00:35:35,925 --> 00:35:41,389
that he didn't want to display
the Reebok logo

629
00:35:41,472 --> 00:35:43,516
that was on his uniform.

630
00:35:45,852 --> 00:35:48,604
<i>Maybe Michael Jordan
did come to the '92 Olympics</i>

631
00:35:48,688 --> 00:35:52,066
<i>with an innocent desire
to recapture his pure love of sport,</i>

632
00:35:52,150 --> 00:35:54,861
<i>but money quickly complicated
the sentimental journey.</i>

633
00:35:55,403 --> 00:35:58,781
<i>Reebok had spent millions
to outfit the teams in Barcelona</i>

634
00:35:58,865 --> 00:36:01,909
<i>and expected all US athletes
to display its logo,</i>

635
00:36:01,993 --> 00:36:04,704
<i>especially the high-profile Dream Team.</i>

636
00:36:08,082 --> 00:36:10,585
Harvey Schiller. What a dick.

637
00:36:10,668 --> 00:36:11,586
Who is that?

638
00:36:11,669 --> 00:36:14,714
The guy who said
if we don't wear our uniforms,

639
00:36:14,797 --> 00:36:18,467
we can't accept our gold medal
and all that stuff.

640
00:36:19,010 --> 00:36:21,596
Is that still a big issue?
They still talking about that?

641
00:36:21,679 --> 00:36:25,224
Nah. They said they are going
to try to hide the Reebok on it.

642
00:36:25,308 --> 00:36:27,643
But they can't hide it
like I'm gonna hide it.

643
00:36:29,353 --> 00:36:31,272
They in for a big fucking surprise.

644
00:36:34,066 --> 00:36:37,945
Michael was so singular
in his competitive drive

645
00:36:38,029 --> 00:36:40,740
and the drive that extended
to his partners, like Nike,

646
00:36:40,823 --> 00:36:45,828
that he could not bear the thought of
wearing the Reebok logo on a global stage,

647
00:36:45,912 --> 00:36:48,289
receiving a gold medal at the Olympics.

648
00:36:50,291 --> 00:36:55,838
So he covered the Reebok logo up
with the United States flag.

649
00:36:55,922 --> 00:36:59,342
<i>Michael Jordan draped
in the American flag...</i>

650
00:36:59,425 --> 00:37:00,593
It was extraordinary.

651
00:37:00,676 --> 00:37:03,346
<i>I think that is not solely
for patriotic reasons.</i>

652
00:37:05,598 --> 00:37:09,894
Here in Barcelona and the Olympics, these
folks have done a job taking basketball,

653
00:37:09,977 --> 00:37:14,190
and Michael Jordan, particularly,
to unbelievable heights.

654
00:37:14,273 --> 00:37:16,692
Michael was the face
of the Dream Team,

655
00:37:16,776 --> 00:37:21,739
and the Dream Team changed everything
about international basketball.

656
00:37:22,490 --> 00:37:25,451
The Dream Team's entirely responsible
for the NBA's profile

657
00:37:25,534 --> 00:37:29,080
taking a massive jump forward.

658
00:37:29,747 --> 00:37:33,668
It just... It shaped how the world
felt about the NBA.

659
00:37:35,044 --> 00:37:36,879
Michael Jordan, the Dream Team,

660
00:37:36,963 --> 00:37:42,551
helped bring sports into that place
of cultural influence globally.

661
00:37:42,635 --> 00:37:45,763
So it wasn't just music that was cool,

662
00:37:45,846 --> 00:37:49,892
it wasn't just fashion in the US
that was translating into other countries.

663
00:37:49,976 --> 00:37:52,353
All of a sudden, it was the NBA.

664
00:37:54,480 --> 00:37:58,734
I think it was the first time that
sports was being sold in a cultural way.

665
00:37:59,443 --> 00:38:01,362
We were selling Americana.

666
00:38:01,445 --> 00:38:06,951
And then what attached to it was this
incredibly handsome, successful player...

667
00:38:07,034 --> 00:38:11,914
his swagger, and people
wanted to be part of that.

668
00:38:16,377 --> 00:38:20,506
After the Olympics,
Michael was the most recognizable,

669
00:38:20,589 --> 00:38:23,676
the most popular sports figure,

670
00:38:23,759 --> 00:38:26,804
but really, cultural figure, in the world.

671
00:38:26,887 --> 00:38:29,307
He was really a global superstar.

672
00:38:29,890 --> 00:38:32,310
Everyone around the world
knew Michael Jordan.

673
00:38:39,233 --> 00:38:40,735
<i>♪ Sometimes I dream ♪</i>

674
00:38:41,402 --> 00:38:43,279
<i>♪ That he is me ♪</i>

675
00:38:43,904 --> 00:38:47,074
<i>♪ You've got to see
That's how I dream to be ♪</i>

676
00:38:48,492 --> 00:38:53,122
Once he got to the point
where it was "Be like Mike"...

677
00:38:53,205 --> 00:38:55,583
<i>♪ If I could be like Mike ♪</i>

678
00:38:55,666 --> 00:38:57,543
...that changed everything for him.

679
00:38:58,377 --> 00:38:59,837
There's pressure to be like Mike.

680
00:38:59,920 --> 00:39:03,841
If you're gonna be like him, you've gotta
be clean, you've gotta be Teflon.

681
00:39:03,924 --> 00:39:07,470
You've gotta be completely spotless
as a person,

682
00:39:07,553 --> 00:39:08,971
and no human being is like that.

683
00:39:09,055 --> 00:39:10,973
<i>- ♪ Be like Mike! ♪
- ♪ Be like Mike! ♪</i>

684
00:39:11,057 --> 00:39:13,768
<i>♪ Like Mike, if I could be like Mike ♪</i>

685
00:39:16,312 --> 00:39:20,691
Any African-American in this society

686
00:39:20,775 --> 00:39:22,985
that sees significant success

687
00:39:24,278 --> 00:39:26,614
has an added burden.

688
00:39:26,697 --> 00:39:30,159
And a lot of times,
America's very quick to embrace

689
00:39:30,242 --> 00:39:34,372
a Michael Jordan or an Oprah Winfrey
or a Barack Obama, uh...

690
00:39:35,164 --> 00:39:40,419
so long as it's understood
that you don't get too controversial

691
00:39:40,503 --> 00:39:43,506
around broader issues of social justice.

692
00:39:43,589 --> 00:39:45,758
Part of the reason
he remained popular is that

693
00:39:45,841 --> 00:39:47,927
he never did anything to piss anybody off.

694
00:39:48,636 --> 00:39:51,972
Probably the most controversial thing
Jordan said in his career

695
00:39:52,056 --> 00:39:55,184
was when Harvey Gantt
was running for Senate

696
00:39:55,267 --> 00:39:57,978
to be the first African-American
from North Carolina

697
00:39:58,062 --> 00:40:00,314
to serve in the US Senate.

698
00:40:00,398 --> 00:40:03,734
Michael would not come out
and endorse or support Gantt

699
00:40:03,818 --> 00:40:07,738
and, uh, was quoted as saying,
"Republicans buy sneakers, too."

700
00:40:09,365 --> 00:40:11,965
<i>Democrats in North Carolina
have nominated Harvey Gantt</i>

701
00:40:12,034 --> 00:40:13,577
<i>as their candidate for the Senate.</i>

702
00:40:13,661 --> 00:40:15,788
<i>If he defeats incumbent Jesse Helms,</i>

703
00:40:15,871 --> 00:40:18,416
<i>Gantt would become
the state's first black senator.</i>

704
00:40:18,499 --> 00:40:22,670
1990 North Carolina Senate race.

705
00:40:22,753 --> 00:40:25,673
You have the infamous Jesse Helms

706
00:40:25,756 --> 00:40:28,676
and an African-American
by the name of Harvey Gantt.

707
00:40:29,510 --> 00:40:31,429
The stakes are really high.

708
00:40:31,512 --> 00:40:35,015
Jesse Helms was a reprehensible figure

709
00:40:35,099 --> 00:40:37,810
in terms of his racism
and conservative politics.

710
00:40:37,893 --> 00:40:39,854
Nothing cool about Jesse Helms.

711
00:40:39,937 --> 00:40:42,565
<i>Jesse Helms can take
full credit or blame</i>

712
00:40:42,648 --> 00:40:45,443
<i>for killing a new National
African-American Museum.</i>

713
00:40:46,026 --> 00:40:48,779
Helms also stood against
the Martin Luther King holiday.

714
00:40:48,863 --> 00:40:51,907
I'm not saying to you that
we wouldn't have segregated schools,

715
00:40:51,991 --> 00:40:54,160
or largely segregated schools,

716
00:40:54,243 --> 00:40:58,289
under a Freedom of Choice plan,
such as I've suggested,

717
00:40:58,372 --> 00:41:02,501
but I will say to you that
that would be the choice.

718
00:41:02,585 --> 00:41:08,424
Michael refuses to do a commercial
to support Harvey Gantt

719
00:41:08,507 --> 00:41:12,720
and the statement that emerges,
"Republicans buy Nikes, too,"

720
00:41:12,803 --> 00:41:15,181
sounds as though Michael is saying,

721
00:41:15,264 --> 00:41:20,603
"My personal wealth
is more important than my politics

722
00:41:20,686 --> 00:41:22,563
as it pertains to the issue of race."

723
00:41:22,646 --> 00:41:24,607
I don't think that statement
needs to be corrected

724
00:41:24,690 --> 00:41:30,654
because I said it in jest on a bus
with Horace Grant and Scottie Pippen

725
00:41:30,738 --> 00:41:33,073
and it was thrown off the cuff.

726
00:41:33,657 --> 00:41:36,619
My mother asked me to do
a PSA for Harvey Gantt.

727
00:41:36,702 --> 00:41:40,247
And I said, "Look, Mom, I'm not speaking
out of pocket about someone I don't know,

728
00:41:40,331 --> 00:41:44,710
but I will send a contribution
to support him," which is what I did.

729
00:41:44,793 --> 00:41:48,589
<i>Conservative incumbent
Jesse Helms won a fourth term,</i>

730
00:41:48,672 --> 00:41:51,425
<i>defeating liberal black Harvey Gantt.</i>

731
00:41:51,509 --> 00:41:54,595
There is no joy
in Mudville tonight.

732
00:41:57,389 --> 00:41:59,069
<i>Gantt was not bitter in defeat,</i>

733
00:41:59,141 --> 00:42:03,145
<i>but this contest proves that race is still
a powerful issue in American politics.</i>

734
00:42:03,229 --> 00:42:04,563
Harvey! Harvey!

735
00:42:04,647 --> 00:42:08,651
Michael did lose some credibility
with an African-American audience

736
00:42:08,734 --> 00:42:13,113
and people were disappointed because
he did not come out and support Gantt.

737
00:42:13,197 --> 00:42:16,742
Everybody in the world
respects Muhammad Ali.

738
00:42:16,825 --> 00:42:19,537
You know why?
Because he stood for something.

739
00:42:19,620 --> 00:42:24,250
He stood for something
even if it meant sacrificing a payday.

740
00:42:24,333 --> 00:42:25,960
We respect that.

741
00:42:26,043 --> 00:42:29,964
Ultimately, Michael Jordan
may be forgotten.

742
00:42:30,047 --> 00:42:31,799
Muhammad Ali won't be forgotten.

743
00:42:33,634 --> 00:42:37,972
I do commend Muhammad Ali
for standing up for what he believed in,

744
00:42:39,014 --> 00:42:41,392
but I never thought of myself
as an activist.

745
00:42:41,475 --> 00:42:43,686
I thought of myself
as a basketball player.

746
00:42:45,312 --> 00:42:50,693
I wasn't a politician when I was playing
my sport. I was focused on my craft.

747
00:42:50,776 --> 00:42:52,236
Was that selfish? Probably.

748
00:42:52,319 --> 00:42:55,406
But that was my energy,
that's where my energy was.

749
00:42:55,489 --> 00:42:57,825
I'll be honest that when...

750
00:42:58,576 --> 00:43:03,455
it was reported that Michael said,
"Republicans buy sneakers, too..."

751
00:43:04,123 --> 00:43:05,165
Uh...

752
00:43:05,833 --> 00:43:08,794
For somebody who was, at that time,

753
00:43:08,877 --> 00:43:12,840
preparing for a career in civil rights law
and in public life

754
00:43:12,923 --> 00:43:15,426
and knowing what Jesse Helms stood for,

755
00:43:16,093 --> 00:43:20,139
you would've wanted to see
Michael push harder on that.

756
00:43:21,307 --> 00:43:22,474
On the other hand,

757
00:43:23,267 --> 00:43:28,939
he was still trying to figure out,
"How am I... managing this image

758
00:43:29,607 --> 00:43:32,693
that has been created around me, um,

759
00:43:32,776 --> 00:43:34,361
and how do I live up to it?"

760
00:43:34,987 --> 00:43:38,115
It's never gonna be enough for everybody.
I know that, I realize that,

761
00:43:38,198 --> 00:43:40,034
'cause everybody has a preconceived idea

762
00:43:40,117 --> 00:43:43,203
in terms of what they think I should do
or what I shouldn't do.

763
00:43:44,913 --> 00:43:48,459
The way that I go about my life
is I set examples.

764
00:43:49,501 --> 00:43:53,672
And if it inspires you, great.
You know, I will continue to do that.

765
00:43:53,756 --> 00:43:57,926
If it doesn't, then maybe I'm not
the person that you should be following.

766
00:44:11,148 --> 00:44:15,986
In '97 and '98, the ticket
requests went through the roof

767
00:44:16,070 --> 00:44:20,157
because there was a question mark,
"Did Michael wanna play or retire?"

768
00:44:21,909 --> 00:44:26,538
That year, we put our tickets on sale
on a Saturday morning, at ten o'clock.

769
00:44:26,622 --> 00:44:29,416
And people lined up
at the Chicago Stadium.

770
00:44:30,376 --> 00:44:33,629
By noon, the entire season was sold out,

771
00:44:34,171 --> 00:44:38,926
but then, every request was a battle
for the rest of the season.

772
00:44:39,009 --> 00:44:45,099
Michael, on most nights, would need
anywhere from 12 to 20 tickets.

773
00:44:45,182 --> 00:44:47,226
Other players would want some.

774
00:44:47,309 --> 00:44:50,521
It was funny, too, because at some point,
I had to limit the players.

775
00:44:50,604 --> 00:44:53,315
We didn't have unlimited tickets
in those days.

776
00:44:56,610 --> 00:44:59,863
Does it matter where they are, man?
Or you want 'em just in the building?

777
00:44:59,947 --> 00:45:01,707
They could be in the locker room
next to God.

778
00:45:03,742 --> 00:45:04,743
Bam.

779
00:45:07,246 --> 00:45:08,956
- Next to who?
- God.

780
00:45:09,498 --> 00:45:12,334
You just got one from him.

781
00:45:13,168 --> 00:45:14,168
Just kidding.

782
00:45:14,753 --> 00:45:17,339
No, he ain't.
No, he ain't, dude. No, he ain't.

783
00:45:17,423 --> 00:45:18,549
Hang on, that's a lie.

784
00:45:18,632 --> 00:45:20,801
- Do not take that off the tape either.
- You better.

785
00:45:20,884 --> 00:45:22,344
- He's not kidding.
- Shit!

786
00:45:22,428 --> 00:45:23,470
Lord, I am with you.

787
00:45:24,138 --> 00:45:25,764
- I was just kidding.
- He's not kidding.

788
00:45:25,848 --> 00:45:27,975
- Don't edit that off.
- Get your ass on outta here.

789
00:45:28,058 --> 00:45:29,601
I gave you a ticket, get the hell out.

790
00:45:29,685 --> 00:45:32,771
Thank you. Make sure y'all don't
edit that off. He ain't kidding.

791
00:45:32,855 --> 00:45:35,649
The road was sometimes
more challenging than at home

792
00:45:35,733 --> 00:45:38,819
because you were dealing
in other people's arenas.

793
00:45:38,902 --> 00:45:41,697
When he played down at Atlanta,
the Bulls played there,

794
00:45:41,780 --> 00:45:44,450
they had more people
than you'd have for a football game

795
00:45:44,533 --> 00:45:46,201
in the Atlanta Dome, just to see Michael.

796
00:45:59,590 --> 00:46:04,136
<i>NBA record 62,046 fans
packed into the Georgia Dome</i>

797
00:46:04,219 --> 00:46:07,973
<i>to see what may have been
Michael Jordan's final game in Atlanta.</i>

798
00:46:08,056 --> 00:46:09,767
Right now, if we had another 15,000 seats,

799
00:46:09,850 --> 00:46:11,810
I believe we could still
sell them for this game.

800
00:46:11,894 --> 00:46:13,437
It's the hottest thing I've ever seen.

801
00:46:13,520 --> 00:46:15,606
All I know is when the tickets
came in this morning,

802
00:46:15,689 --> 00:46:18,192
my wife ran downstairs
and she was crying, she was so happy.

803
00:46:18,275 --> 00:46:19,275
So, I'm the hero.

804
00:46:20,652 --> 00:46:22,237
<i>Oh!</i>

805
00:46:22,321 --> 00:46:25,824
<i>There's nothing you can do about that.
See that's Michael Jordan at his best.</i>

806
00:46:25,908 --> 00:46:30,662
Everywhere you went,
people wanted tickets,

807
00:46:30,746 --> 00:46:32,706
but it became overwhelming.

808
00:46:32,790 --> 00:46:35,125
We gonna see Michael Jordan!

809
00:46:36,460 --> 00:46:38,921
This is what you call a Pope
and Jesus phenomenon.

810
00:46:41,673 --> 00:46:44,009
<i>♪ Ah ha, hush that fuss ♪</i>

811
00:46:44,092 --> 00:46:46,178
<i>♪ Everybody move to the back of the bus ♪</i>

812
00:46:46,261 --> 00:46:48,722
<i>♪ Do you wanna bump and slump with us? ♪</i>

813
00:46:48,806 --> 00:46:51,016
<i>♪ We the type of people
Make the club get crunk ♪</i>

814
00:46:51,099 --> 00:46:53,310
<i>♪ Ah ha, hush that fuss ♪</i>

815
00:46:53,393 --> 00:46:55,979
<i>♪ Everybody move
To the back of the bus... ♪</i>

816
00:46:56,063 --> 00:46:58,690
We saved a lot of money

817
00:46:58,774 --> 00:47:01,777
and we traveled 24 hours
to see Chicago Bulls.

818
00:47:01,860 --> 00:47:03,420
It's a dream!

819
00:47:03,487 --> 00:47:05,322
Tonight's game is sold out.

820
00:47:05,405 --> 00:47:08,826
Do not purchase tickets
from scalpers on Seventh Avenue.

821
00:47:08,909 --> 00:47:10,118
They are counterfeit.

822
00:47:10,202 --> 00:47:13,413
And everybody in the world
begged me for tickets.

823
00:47:13,497 --> 00:47:17,334
Movie stars would come in
and celebrities would come in.

824
00:47:17,417 --> 00:47:18,877
You got to know people.

825
00:47:19,419 --> 00:47:20,629
I can beg. I'm a beggar.

826
00:47:20,712 --> 00:47:22,673
If there's tickets to be gotten,
I will find 'em.

827
00:47:22,756 --> 00:47:25,384
<i>♪ Say ah ha, hush that fuss ♪</i>

828
00:47:25,467 --> 00:47:27,636
<i>♪ Everybody move to the back of the bus ♪</i>

829
00:47:27,719 --> 00:47:30,180
<i>♪ Do you wanna bump and slump with us? ♪</i>

830
00:47:30,264 --> 00:47:32,304
<i>♪ We the type of people
Make the club get crunk... ♪</i>

831
00:47:32,349 --> 00:47:35,519
People expect him to still put on a show
and he does that every night.

832
00:47:35,602 --> 00:47:38,897
Hey, look, I wanna be like Mike also.

833
00:47:39,940 --> 00:47:42,568
What up, fighter?

834
00:47:45,320 --> 00:47:46,780
Michael doesn't pass me the ball.

835
00:47:46,864 --> 00:47:49,408
- You heard it here first.
- He doesn't pass me the ball at all.

836
00:47:49,491 --> 00:47:51,660
I want Michael to play
as long as he wants.

837
00:47:51,743 --> 00:47:52,995
He's at the top of his game.

838
00:47:53,078 --> 00:47:55,914
It's a shame what Krause and Reinsdorf
are doing. I don't understand.

839
00:47:55,998 --> 00:47:58,333
The similarity between
the Bulls and <i>Seinfeld?</i>

840
00:47:59,293 --> 00:48:01,420
The show of the '90s,
the team of the '90s,

841
00:48:01,503 --> 00:48:05,173
and I'm trying to make quitting
the move of the '90s.

842
00:48:05,757 --> 00:48:06,884
Let the new people in.

843
